1 Imagini, chi bene intender cupe 2 quel ch’i’ or vidi—e ritegna l’image, 3 mentre ch’io dico, come ferma rupe—,
4 quindici stelle che ’n diverse plage 5 lo ciel avvivan di tanto sereno 6 che soperchia de l’aere ogne compage;
7 imagini quel carro a cu’ il seno 8 basta del nostro cielo e notte e giorno, 9 sì ch’al volger del temo non vien meno;
10 imagini la bocca di quel corno 11 che si comincia in punta de lo stelo 12 a cui la prima rota va dintorno,
13 aver fatto di sé due segni in cielo, 14 qual fece la figliuola di Minoi 15 allora che sentì di morte il gelo;
16 e l’un ne l’altro aver li raggi suoi, 17 e amendue girarsi per maniera 18 che l’uno andasse al primo e l’altro al poi;
19 e avrà quasi l’ombra de la vera 20 costellazione e de la doppia danza 21 che circulava il punto dov’ io era:
22 poi ch’è tanto di là da nostra usanza, 23 quanto di là dal mover de la Chiana 24 si move il ciel che tutti li altri avanza.

query.result:
**English:**
1 Imagine, if you can truly understand 2 what I saw then—and hold the image, 3 as I speak, like a solid rock—,
4 fifteen stars that in different regions 5 enliven the sky with such serenity 6 that they surpass every part of the air;
7 imagine that chariot whose axle 8 spans our sky both night and day, 9 so that it does not wane as the pole turns;
10 imagine the mouth of that horn 11 that begins at the tip of the axis 12 around which the first wheel turns,
13 having made two signs of itself in the sky, 14 like the daughter of Minos did 15 when she felt the chill of death;
16 and the one having its rays in the other, 17 and both turning in such a way 18 that one went before and the other after;
19 and it will have almost the shadow of the true 20 constellation and of the double dance 21 that circled the point where I was:
22 since it is as far beyond our experience 23 as the sky that surpasses all others 24 is beyond the movement of the Chiana.
**Old English:**
1 Wena ðu ðe wel cunne ongietan deope 2 ðæt ðe ic ða geseah—and geheald ða gesyhðe, 3 swa swa ic secge, swa steapne stan—,
4 fiftene steorran ðe on mislicum stowum 5 ðone heofon alifdon mid swilcum serene 6 ðæt oferfleow ðæs lyftes æghwylce gemet;
7 wena ðu ðone cræt ðæs ðæs bosm 8 genihtsumað ure heofonas nihtes and dæges, 9 swa ðæt hit ne awent for ðæs temes hweorfun;
10 wena ðu ðæs hornes muð ðe onginð æt ðæs stelan ende 11 ðæs ðe ðæt forma hweol ymb cyrreð,
12 habban geworht twegen tacnu on ðam heofone, 13 swa swa ðæs Minoises dohtor dyde 14 ða ðe heo ðæs deaðes cele fyligde;
15 and ðæt an on ðam oðrum hæfde his leoman, 16 and ægðer ymbcerde on ða wisan 17 ðæt ðæt an eode æt ðam forman and ðæt oðer æt ðam æfteran;
18 and hit hæfde nean ða scadu ðære soðan 19 steorran gesomnunge and ðære twyfealdan dancinge 20 ðe ymbcerde ðone stede ðær ic wæs:
21 forðæm hit is swa feor fram ure gewunan, 22 swa swa hit is fram ðæs Clanan hryre 23 ðæt heofon ðe ealle ða oðre oferglint.

